{ "nbformat": 4, "nbformat_minor": 5, "metadata": { "colab": { "name": "Phase-Sensitive OCT Lecture", "provenance": [] }, "kernelspec": { "name": "python3", "display_name": "Python 3" }, "language_info": { "name": "python", "version": "3.x" } }, "cells": [ { "cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": [ "# Phase-Sensitive OCT — Lecture and Colab Notebook\n\nThis notebook is lecture-style and Colab-ready. It explains the physical principle of phase-sensitive OCT, shows the basic processing pipeline, includes a simulation you can run, and provides utilities to load real complex tomograms saved as NumPy .npy files. Use Runtime -> Change runtime type -> Python 3 to run in Colab." ] }, { "cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": [ "## Learning objectives\n- Derive and use the relation between complex phase difference and axial displacement: $\Delta z = (\lambda_0 / 4\pi) \Delta\phi$.\n- Implement a simple PS-OCT pipeline: complex demodulation → phase difference → unwrapping → masking → displacement mapping.\n- Run simulations to explore SNR, decorrelation, and drift." ] }, { "cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": [ "## Physical principle (short)\nOCT provides the complex analytic signal $S(z,x,t)$. For two frames $S_1$ and $S_2$ the cross-product\n$$C(z,x)=\mathrm{conj}(S_1)\cdot S_2$$\nhas phase $\Delta\phi=\arg(C)=4\pi\Delta z/\lambda_0$, so $\Delta z=(\lambda_0/4\pi)\Delta\phi$.\nPhase measures sub-wavelength axial motion but requires adequate SNR and low decorrelation." ] }, { "cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": [ "# Section: imports and utilities\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nfrom scipy.ndimage import gaussian_filter\n\ndef imshow_map(img, title='', cmap='twilight', vmin=None, vmax=None, aspect='auto'):\n    plt.imshow(img, aspect=aspect, cmap=cmap, vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax)\n    plt.title(title)\n    plt.colorbar()\n    plt.xlabel('Lateral')\n    plt.ylabel('Depth')\n    plt.gca().invert_yaxis()\n\ndef phase_to_displacement(phase, lambda0=1300e-9):\n    return (phase * lambda0) / (4.0 * np.pi)\n" ] }, { "cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": [ "# Section: simulate two complex B-scans with axial motion\ndef simulate_two_frames(nz=512, nx=128, n_scatterers=30, lambda0=1300e-9, max_disp_nm=50, snr_db=30, rng_seed=42):\n    rng = np.random.default_rng(rng_seed)\n    z_max = 3e-3\n    z = np.linspace(0, z_max, nz)\n    frame1 = np.zeros((nz, nx), dtype=np.complex128)\n    for ix in range(nx):\n        depths = rng.uniform(0.05*z_max, 0.95*z_max, size=n_scatterers)\n        amps = rng.uniform(0.3, 1.0, size=n_scatterers)\n        phases = rng.uniform(0, 2*np.pi, size=n_scatterers)\n        for a, d, ph in zip(amps, depths, phases):\n            iz = int((d / z_max) * (nz-1))\n            sigma = max(1, nz * 0.002)\n            profile = a * np.exp(-0.5 * ((np.arange(nz) - iz)/sigma)**2)\n            frame1[:, ix] += profile * np.exp(1j*ph)\n    norm = np.max(np.abs(frame1))\n    if norm > 0:\n        frame1 /= norm\n    max_disp_m = max_disp_nm * 1e-9\n    disp_map = max_disp_m * 0.5 * np.sin(2*np.pi*np.arange(nx)/nx*2.0)\n    delta_phi = (4.0 * np.pi / lambda0) * disp_map[np.newaxis, :]\n    decorrelation = rng.normal(scale=0.05, size=frame1.shape)\n    frame2 = np.abs(frame1) * np.exp(1j * (np.angle(frame1) + delta_phi + decorrelation))\n    if snr_db is not None:\n        signal_power = np.mean(np.abs(frame1)**2)\n        snr = 10**(snr_db/10.0)\n        noise_power = signal_power / snr\n        noise_std = np.sqrt(noise_power/2)\n        noise1 = noise_std * (rng.normal(size=frame1.shape) + 1j*rng.normal(size=frame1.shape))\n        noise2 = noise_std * (rng.normal(size=frame2.shape) + 1j*rng.normal(size=frame2.shape))\n        frame1 += noise1\n        frame2 += noise2\n    return frame1, frame2, z\n" ] }, { "cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": [ "# Section: processing pipeline functions\ndef complex_cross_phase(frame1, frame2):\n    cross = np.conj(frame1) * frame2\n    return np.angle(cross)\n\ndef unwrap_phase(phase, axis=0):\n    un = np.unwrap(phase, axis=axis)\n    un = np.unwrap(un, axis=1-axis)\n    return un\n\ndef mask_by_amplitude(frame1, frame2, threshold_ratio=0.05, smooth_sigma=1.0):\n    amplitude = np.sqrt(np.abs(frame1) * np.abs(frame2))\n    amp_smooth = gaussian_filter(amplitude, sigma=(smooth_sigma, smooth_sigma))\n    thresh = threshold_ratio * np.max(amp_smooth)\n    return amp_smooth, amp_smooth > thresh\n" ] }, { "cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": [ "# Section: lecture demo (run this cell to see results)\nf1, f2, z = simulate_two_frames(nz=512, nx=160, n_scatterers=40, max_disp_nm=80, snr_db=30)\namp, mask = mask_by_amplitude(f1, f2, threshold_ratio=0.03, smooth_sigma=1.0)\nraw_phase = complex_cross_phase(f1, f2)\nunwrapped = unwrap_phase(raw_phase, axis=0)\nunwrapped_masked = np.where(mask, unwrapped, 0.0)\ndisp = phase_to_displacement(unwrapped_masked)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(16,4))\nplt.subplot(1,4,1)\nimshow_map(20*np.log10(amp+1e-12), title='Amplitude (dB)', cmap='gray')\nplt.subplot(1,4,2)\nimshow_map(raw_phase, title='Raw phase (rad)')\nplt.subplot(1,4,3)\nimshow_map(unwrapped_masked, title='Unwrapped phase (rad)')\nplt.subplot(1,4,4)\nimshow_map(disp*1e9, title='Axial displacement (nm)', cmap='RdBu_r')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\nprint('Max recovered displacement (nm):', np.nanmax(disp)*1e9)\n" ] }, { "cell_type": "code", "execution_count": null, "metadata": {}, "outputs": [], "source": [ "# Section: load .npy complex tomogram (exercise)\ndef load_npy_tomogram(path, frame_pair=(0,1), lambda0=1300e-9):\n    data = np.load(path)\n    if data.ndim == 2:\n        raise ValueError('Need two frames: provide (nz,nx,2) or (nz,nx,nFrames)')\n    if data.ndim == 3:\n        if data.shape[2] == 2:\n            f1 = data[:, :, 0].astype(np.complex128)\n            f2 = data[:, :, 1].astype(np.complex128)\n        else:\n            i0, i1 = frame_pair\n            f1 = data[:, :, i0].astype(np.complex128)\n            f2 = data[:, :, i1].astype(np.complex128)\n    amp, mask = mask_by_amplitude(f1, f2, threshold_ratio=0.03, smooth_sigma=1.0)\n    raw_phase = complex_cross_phase(f1, f2)\nunwrapped = unwrap_phase(raw_phase, axis=0)\nunwrapped_masked = np.where(mask, unwrapped, 0.0)\ndisp = phase_to_displacement(unwrapped_masked, lambda0=lambda0)\n    nz = f1.shape[0]\n    z = np.linspace(0, 3e-3, nz)\n    return amp, raw_phase, unwrapped_masked, disp, z\n\n# In Colab you can upload with:\n# from google.colab import files\n# uploaded = files.upload()\n# then call: amp, raw_phase, unwrapped, disp, z = load_npy_tomogram(uploaded_filename)\n" ] }, { "cell_type": "markdown", "metadata": {}, "source": [ "## Exercises and next steps\n- Run the demo with different SNR and max_disp_nm values to see phase noise and wrapping.\n- Add a global phase drift term to frame2 and implement drift removal by subtracting the mean phase in an ROI.\n- Replace unwrap_phase with a 2D quality-guided unwrapping algorithm for improved results.\n- Convert displacement to velocity if frame time Δt is known.\n\n### References\nAdd your preferred references (Leitgeb, Vakoc, Wojtkowski, etc.) in this cell." ] } ] }